TY  - JOUR
T1  - Employee Recognition and Performance: A Field Experiment
AU  - Bradler, Christiane
AU  - Dur, Robert
AU  - Neckermann, Susanne
AU  - Non, Arjan
Y1  - 2016/02/09
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2016/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2015.2291
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2015.2291
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 3085
EP  - 3099
VL  - 62
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper reports the results from a controlled field experiment designed to investigate the causal effect of unannounced, public recognition on employee performance. We hired more than 300 employees to work on a three-hour data-entry task. In a random sample of work groups, workers unexpectedly received recognition after two hours of work. We find that recognition increases subsequent performance substantially, and particularly when recognition is exclusively provided to the best performers. Remarkably, workers who did not receive recognition are mainly responsible for this performance increase. Our results are consistent with workers having a preference for conformity and being reciprocal at the same time. Data, as supplemental material, are available at http://dx.doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2015.2291. This paper was accepted by John List, behavioral economics.
AB  - This paper reports the results from a controlled field experiment designed to investigate the causal effect of unannounced, public recognition on employee performance. We hired more than 300 employees to work on a three-hour data-entry task. In a random sample of work groups, workers unexpectedly received recognition after two hours of work. We find that recognition increases subsequent performance substantially, and particularly when recognition is exclusively provided to the best performers. Remarkably, workers who did not receive recognition are mainly responsible for this performance increase. Our results are consistent with workers having a preference for conformity and being reciprocal at the same time. Data, as supplemental material, are available at http://dx.doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2015.2291. This paper was accepted by John List, behavioral economics.
