T1  - A Reconsideration of Gender Differences in Risk Attitudes
AU  - Filippin, Antonio
AU  - Crosetto, Paolo
Y1  - 2016/02/16
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2016/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2015.2294
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2015.2294
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 3138
EP  - 3160
VL  - 62
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper reconsiders the wide agreement that females are more risk averse than males. We survey the existing experimental literature, finding that significance and magnitude of gender differences are task specific. We gather data from 54 replications of the Holt and Laury risk elicitation method, involving about 7,000 subjects. Gender differences appear in less than 10% of the studies and are significant but negligible in magnitude once all the data are pooled. Results are confirmed by structural estimations, which also support a constant relative risk aversion representation of preferences. Gender differences correlate with the presence of a safe option and fixed probabilities in the elicitation method. This paper was accepted by John List, behavioral economics.
AB  - This paper reconsiders the wide agreement that females are more risk averse than males. We survey the existing experimental literature, finding that significance and magnitude of gender differences are task specific. We gather data from 54 replications of the Holt and Laury risk elicitation method, involving about 7,000 subjects. Gender differences appear in less than 10% of the studies and are significant but negligible in magnitude once all the data are pooled. Results are confirmed by structural estimations, which also support a constant relative risk aversion representation of preferences. Gender differences correlate with the presence of a safe option and fixed probabilities in the elicitation method. This paper was accepted by John List, behavioral economics.
